<span id="freeTextContainer670184964414027396">I first heard about this book at the National Museum of Nuclear Science &amp; History in Albuquerque, a few days after j and I visited Los Alamos, which is one the strangest places I&apos;ve ever been. My dad has also been giving me all sorts of information about the aftermath of the Fukushima disaster, since he lives relatively close to Japan. So, I&apos;ve kind of been obsessed with nuclear science and history for the last six months.<br/><br/>This book is really fascinating and tremendously important, and I highly r</span>
  <span id="freeText670184964414027396" style="display:none">I first heard about this book at the National Museum of Nuclear Science &amp; History in Albuquerque, a few days after j and I visited Los Alamos, which is one the strangest places I've ever been. My dad has also been giving me all sorts of information about the aftermath of the Fukushima disaster, since he lives relatively close to Japan. So, I've kind of been obsessed with nuclear science and history for the last six months.<br /><br />This book is really fascinating and tremendously important, and I highly recommend it to everyone. I can't stop thinking and talking about it. I wish I still had more of it to read. Schlosser does such a great job researching and presenting dense and complex information, and I feel a sincere appreciation to him for writing this book.</span>
